      "acceptanceCriteria": "FDA-validated Ansys Mechanical release with documented V&V test suite; version-controlled analysis scripts under ISO 13485 QMS.",
      "rationale": "All three modeling groups (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) used commercially released, FDA Q-Sub-cleared FEA solvers. Version control logs and regression test reports were reviewed. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2 for a Class II, medium-influence COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from ASME V&V 10 suite solved to within 1% of analytical solutions.",
      "rationale": "Standard beam-bending and contact patch benchmarks were executed for each solver instance. All results within 0.8% of closed-form solutions. Required and achieved levels are equal; criterion met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating <2% change in QoI between successive refinements; GCI < 5%.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed on the pedicle screw shank and rod-screw interface. Grid Convergence Index for construct stiffness was 1.7%; for yield force 2.3%. Both below the 5% threshold. Achieved level 3 matches required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force and displacement residuals converge to <1e-5 relative norm; energy balance verified.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear Newton-Raphson iterations converged to residual norms below 1e-6 for all load steps. Energy balance errors were less than 0.05% across all 11 virtual specimens. Criterion met at required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of simulation setup by analyst not involved in model construction; documented checklist completed.",
      "rationale": "Each modeling group performed an internal cross-check by a second qualified engineer using a standardized setup checklist. Boundary condition application, material assignment, and contact definitions were independently verified. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastic-plastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening; contact modeled with penalty or augmented Lagrangian; geometric nonlinearity enabled.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V rod and screw were modeled with bilinear isotropic hardening (Ramberg-Osgood fit to tensile coupon data). Large-deformation kinematics enabled. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at rod-screw interface. Model form is well-established for metallic implant bending; level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties derived from lot-specific tensile testing of same material batch used in bench specimens; geometry from calibrated CMM measurements.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and ultimate tensile strength were measured from three tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V rod stock used in the bench test constructs. Screw geometry was digitized via CMM to within 5 µm. Input uncertainty propagated using Monte Carlo (n=1000); coefficient of variation on stiffness QoI was 1.8%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production lots; dimensional inspection of each specimen reported.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production lots. Each construct was dimensionally inspected prior to testing; all within drawing tolerances. Sample size exceeds the minimum of 10 specified for this risk level. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing performed under at least two independent laboratory conditions or two load configurations; environmental controls documented.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes R&D) under ASTM F1717 standard conditions. However, only a single load configuration (static compression-bending at 5 mm/min) was evaluated. The absence of a second load rate or cyclic preconditioning condition limits this factor to achieved level 2 against a required level of 3. This shortfall is acknowledged; the overall credibility assessment proceeds because all other factors meet or exceed requirements and the E/uval criterion is satisfied across all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstrated traceability between FEA boundary conditions and experimental fixture geometry; crosshead displacement rate mapped to quasi-static loading assumption.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 fixture geometry was replicated in the FEA model to within 0.1 mm using CAD drawings supplied by the test laboratory. The 5 mm/min crosshead rate produces negligible inertial effects (verified by ratio of kinetic to strain energy < 0.1%); quasi-static assumption valid. Input parameter equivalency confirmed at level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all primary QoIs; percent difference < 10%.",
      "rationale": "For construct stiffness: mean FEA 187.4 N/mm vs. experimental 191.2 N/mm (2.0% difference; E/uval = 0.84). For yield force: mean FEA 612 N vs. experimental 624 N (1.9%; E/uval = 1.12). For force at 40 mm: mean FEA 743 N vs. experimental 758 N (2.0%; E/uval = 1.31). All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly correspond to regulatory submission endpoints and clinical failure modes (construct stiffness, yield force, displacement at failure).",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in the FDA guidance on pedicle screw system submissions and are directly linked to the clinical risk of construct failure leading to revision surgery. The QoIs are identical between the simulation and the experimental protocol. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Qualitative and quantitative assessment of whether the validation experimental conditions bracket the intended clinical use envelope.",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive qualitative assessment was performed to evaluate the degree to which the ASTM F1717 bench test environment represents the in vivo spinal loading scenario for a non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct. The validation activities replicate the regulatory test standard that serves as a surrogate for worst-case clinical loading, and the two-laboratory design increases confidence in reproducibility. Subject matter experts from FDA CDRH, DePuy Synthes, and an independent biomechanics consultant reviewed and concurred that the validation scope is appropriate for the intended COU. The consensus judgment is that the validation activities are sufficiently relevant to support the Accepted decision, with the understanding that in vivo loading is more complex and that the F1717 protocol is an accepted regulatory surrogate. This factor was evaluated through structured expert elicitation and documented review rather than a graduated scoring exercise, reflecting the inherently qualitative nature of relevance judgments at the COU boundary."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single shortfall (Test conditions, achieved level 2 vs. required level 3) is offset by the strong quantitative output comparison results (E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs, percent differences < 2.5%) and by the two-laboratory design that partially compensates for the absence of a second load configuration. The overall credibility of the FEA model ensemble is judged sufficient to support regulatory submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending conditions.",
